---
import ResourcePage from '../../components/ResourcePage.astro';

const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "MedicalWebPage",
    "name": "ADHD Resources",
    "description": "Educational resources about ADHD symptoms, executive functioning, treatment options, and support for children, adolescents, and adults.",
    "url": "https://empowerpsychiatryil.com/resources/adhd-resources",
    "about": "ADHD",
    "provider": {
      "@type": "MedicalBusiness",
      "name": "Empower Psychiatry",
      "url": "https://empowerpsychiatryil.com",
      "telephone": "+1-630-326-3840",
      "address": {
        "@type": "PostalAddress",
        "streetAddress": "303 E Army Trail Rd, Suite 111",
        "addressLocality": "Bloomingdale",
        "addressRegion": "IL",
        "postalCode": "60108"
      }
    }
  }
];
---

<ResourcePage
  title="ADHD Resources"
  description="Educational resources about ADHD symptoms, executive functioning, treatment options, and support for children, adolescents, and adults."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="resource-main-content reveal">
    <h2>Understanding ADHD</h2>
    <p>
      Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is a neurodevelopmental condition that can affect
      attention, organization, impulse control, emotional regulation, and daily functioning. ADHD may present
      differently in children, adolescents, and adults, and symptoms can range from mild to significantly
      disruptive.
    </p>
    <p>
      Many individuals with ADHD experience challenges with executive functioning, including time management,
      task initiation, planning, memory, and maintaining focus. While ADHD is commonly identified during
      childhood, many adults are diagnosed later in life after years of struggling with concentration,
      productivity, or emotional overwhelm.
    </p>

    <h2>Common Symptoms</h2>
    <ul class="resource-list">
      <li>Difficulty maintaining attention or completing tasks</li>
      <li>Forgetfulness and disorganization</li>
      <li>Restlessness or excessive movement</li>
      <li>Impulsivity and difficulty waiting</li>
      <li>Frequent procrastination</li>
      <li>Emotional dysregulation or frustration intolerance</li>
      <li>Difficulty managing school, work, or responsibilities</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Treatment Approaches</h2>
    <p>
      ADHD treatment is individualized and may include medication management, behavioral therapy, parent
      coaching, academic support strategies, and lifestyle interventions. Treatment plans often focus on
      improving organization, reducing stress, strengthening coping skills, and supporting long-term
      functioning.
    </p>
    <p>
      For children and adolescents, collaboration between families, schools, therapists, and medical providers
      can play an important role in successful outcomes. Adults with ADHD may also benefit from executive
      functioning coaching, workplace accommodations, and structured routines.
    </p>

    <h2>Support for Families</h2>
    <p>
      Families often benefit from education about ADHD and practical strategies for communication, structure,
      and emotional support. Consistent routines, clear expectations, positive reinforcement, and patience can
      make a meaningful difference in helping children and teens build confidence and resilience.
    </p>
  </article>

  <aside class="resource-sidebar reveal">
    <div class="resource-sidebar-card">
      <h3>Trusted Organizations</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://chadd.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CHADD</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/topics/attention-deficit-hyperactivity-disorder-adhd" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NIMH ADHD</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/adhd/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CDC ADHD Resources</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="resource-sidebar-card">
      <h3>Local & Crisis Support</h3>
      <p>
        For urgent emotional support, call or text 988 for the Suicide & Crisis Lifeline. Residents in Addison,
        Bloomingdale, DuPage County, and the greater Chicagoland area may also benefit from local counseling
        centers, hospitals, and emergency mental health services.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="resource-sidebar-card">
      <h3>When To Seek Help</h3>
      <p>
        Consider professional evaluation if symptoms are affecting work, school, sleep, relationships, emotional
        wellbeing, or daily functioning. Early support and treatment can improve long-term outcomes and quality
        of life.
      </p>
    </div>
  </aside>
</ResourcePage>
